hood to welfare state expansion over the course of the twentieth century and it raises new questions about the legitimacy of religiously inspired neo-patriarchy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFatherhoodvCase studies. 0aFatherhoodxCase studiesxSwedenxUnited States. 0aFatherhoodxSocial aspectsxSweden. 0aFatherhoodxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aFatherhoodxSocial aspectszSweden. 0aFatherhoodxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aFathersxServices forxSweden. 0aFathersxServices forxUnited States. 0aFathersxServices forzSweden. 0aFathersxServices forzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh  aNordic feminism.  aPatriarchy.  achild maintenance.  afatherhood.  aindividualisation.  aparental leave.  awelfare regimes.1 aRush, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499160940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784991609423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784991609/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles